### The Destination: Understanding Sociosexuality

While this page merely points the way, its ultimate destination is the concept of [Sociosexuality](/Sociosexuality). In brief, and because I'm obligated to provide context, [sociosexuality](/Sociosexuality) refers to an individual difference in the willingness to engage in sexual activity outside of a committed relationship. It's a measure of one's comfort with casual sex, ranging from restricted (unwilling to engage in sex without closeness and commitment) to unrestricted (comfortable with sex without such emotional ties). This construct is typically assessed using a self-report questionnaire known as the [Sociosexual Orientation Inventory](/Sociosexual_Orientation_Inventory) (SOI), which probes attitudes, desires, and past behaviors related to uncommitted sexual activity. The concept has been widely studied in [evolutionary psychology](/Evolutionary_psychology) and [social psychology](/Social_psychology) to understand variations in mating strategies and [sexual behavior](/Sexual_behavior) across individuals and cultures. It’s a topic that, much like this redirect, exists to categorize and define human tendencies, albeit with significantly more nuance and fewer lines of code.

